00:00:30.356 --> 00:00:31.686 A:middle
&gt;&gt; OLIVIER BONNET: Good
afternoon and welcome

00:00:31.686 --> 00:00:34.416 A:middle
to Session 704 What's
New in CloudKit.

00:00:35.156 --> 00:00:36.246 A:middle
My name is Olivier.

00:00:36.246 --> 00:00:39.006 A:middle
I'm the Engineering Manager
for the iCloud Client teams.

00:00:39.976 --> 00:00:44.656 A:middle
So a year ago we introduced
CloudKits a brand new framework

00:00:44.966 --> 00:00:48.476 A:middle
for you as developers to
harness of the power of iCloud.

00:00:49.156 --> 00:00:54.056 A:middle
We built a number of
the iOS 8 new features

00:00:54.056 --> 00:00:55.186 A:middle
on top of CloudKits.

00:00:55.526 --> 00:00:59.266 A:middle
Most visibly iCloud Drive and
iCloud Photo Library were built

00:00:59.736 --> 00:01:03.536 A:middle
from the ground up on top of
CloudKit but Mail Drop, HomeKit,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:59.736 --> 00:01:03.536 A:middle
from the ground up on top of
CloudKit but Mail Drop, HomeKit,

00:01:04.096 --> 00:01:07.226 A:middle
Safari history syncing, and
call history syncing were also

00:01:07.226 --> 00:01:08.056 A:middle
using CloudKit.

00:01:08.576 --> 00:01:12.416 A:middle
So a year later,
what have we seen?

00:01:13.306 --> 00:01:17.106 A:middle
We have uploaded over
240 billion records.

00:01:18.176 --> 00:01:22.426 A:middle
We saved over 250 petabytes
of assets and that's coming

00:01:22.426 --> 00:01:25.156 A:middle
from over 300 million users.

00:01:26.516 --> 00:01:28.326 A:middle
So really, we couldn't
be happier

00:01:28.326 --> 00:01:32.716 A:middle
with how this has turned
out, with how reliable

00:01:32.716 --> 00:01:34.566 A:middle
and stable CloudKit
has been for us.

00:01:35.356 --> 00:01:39.856 A:middle
So this year, we're going to add
a couple more features to that.

00:01:40.476 --> 00:01:44.006 A:middle
Notes is now using
CloudKit on iOS,

00:01:44.276 --> 00:01:47.716 A:middle
and OS X to synchronize your
notes between your devices.

00:01:48.936 --> 00:01:50.806 A:middle
The new app we introduces
yesterday,

00:01:50.806 --> 00:01:55.146 A:middle
News is entirely built on
the CloudKit public database.

00:01:56.296 --> 00:01:59.506 A:middle
Even the WWDC app is now
using CloudKit this year.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:00.016 --> 00:02:02.276 A:middle
And last but not
least iCloud Backup,

00:02:03.016 --> 00:02:06.406 A:middle
was ported in iOS
9 to use CloudKit.

00:02:07.216 --> 00:02:09.636 A:middle
So this is actually -- this
one is actually a bigger deal

00:02:09.636 --> 00:02:12.306 A:middle
than it seems because iCloud
Backup is our biggest service

00:02:12.786 --> 00:02:16.396 A:middle
in terms of number of users,
amount of data, and the number

00:02:16.396 --> 00:02:19.796 A:middle
of requests per seconds.

00:02:19.906 --> 00:02:22.776 A:middle
We've also heard some good
feedback from you as developers.

00:02:23.316 --> 00:02:26.616 A:middle
For instance, from Hipstamatic,
"With CloudKit, we were able

00:02:26.616 --> 00:02:28.066 A:middle
to focus on building our app,

00:02:28.216 --> 00:02:30.036 A:middle
and even squeeze
in a few extras."

00:02:30.656 --> 00:02:33.036 A:middle
So that is exactly
why we built CloudKit.

00:02:33.876 --> 00:02:37.386 A:middle
To enable you as developers to
focus on building great apps,

00:02:37.536 --> 00:02:40.596 A:middle
building awesome user
experience, without having

00:02:40.596 --> 00:02:43.286 A:middle
to set up a server, without
having to operate it,

00:02:43.676 --> 00:02:46.486 A:middle
without having to
be on call 24/7.

00:02:47.956 --> 00:02:52.306 A:middle
AgileBits is using CloudKit to
synchronize one password data.

00:02:52.306 --> 00:02:53.326 A:middle
They're happy with it.

00:02:53.406 --> 00:02:56.086 A:middle
Here's what they're saying:
"CloudKit is very fast,

00:02:56.086 --> 00:02:59.786 A:middle
efficient, and makes it easy to
detect and troubleshoot errors."

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:03:00.486 --> 00:03:05.586 A:middle
Again, that was one of our
design goals with CloudKit.

00:03:06.106 --> 00:03:09.286 A:middle
If there's an error in the
daemon, on the network,

00:03:09.286 --> 00:03:12.356 A:middle
or on the server side, we will
return that error to your app

00:03:12.746 --> 00:03:15.786 A:middle
and your app is in
charge of handling it,

00:03:15.786 --> 00:03:19.126 A:middle
retrying it, if it makes sense.

00:03:19.316 --> 00:03:23.076 A:middle
Last but not least, IconFactory:
"One of the best parts

00:03:23.076 --> 00:03:26.236 A:middle
about CloudKit is there's no
complicated sign-in process

00:03:26.236 --> 00:03:26.846 A:middle
or setup."

00:03:27.606 --> 00:03:29.636 A:middle
Again that was one of out goals.

00:03:30.056 --> 00:03:34.406 A:middle
Make it possible to enable
completely seamless user

00:03:34.406 --> 00:03:36.726 A:middle
experience, no account creation,

00:03:36.726 --> 00:03:38.926 A:middle
no password to enter
or remember.

00:03:40.676 --> 00:03:42.496 A:middle
In addition to this
good feedback,

00:03:42.496 --> 00:03:45.096 A:middle
we also heard some questions
from you as developers.

00:03:45.666 --> 00:03:47.326 A:middle
So last year, we
introduced CloudKit.

00:03:47.326 --> 00:03:49.096 A:middle
We said it was free with limits.

