[Applause].

00:04:26.086 --> 00:04:26.636 A:middle
&gt;&gt; ERIC KRUGLER: Thank you.

00:04:26.726 --> 00:04:27.826 A:middle
Well, thank you, Olivier.

00:04:28.016 --> 00:04:30.536 A:middle
It's terrific to be here
this afternoon to talk to you

00:04:30.536 --> 00:04:32.166 A:middle
about what's new in CloudKit.

00:04:32.836 --> 00:04:34.786 A:middle
Let's start by answering
that first question.

00:04:34.786 --> 00:04:35.606 A:middle
What does it cost?

00:04:36.186 --> 00:04:39.226 A:middle
We are going to look at CloudKit
usage and pricing but to get

00:04:39.226 --> 00:04:40.136 A:middle
into that, we first need

00:04:40.136 --> 00:04:42.346 A:middle
to understand the
CloudKit architecture.

00:04:42.746 --> 00:04:46.556 A:middle
So when you use CloudKit,
all of your data is stored

00:04:46.556 --> 00:04:47.916 A:middle
in your CloudKit container.

00:04:48.266 --> 00:04:50.256 A:middle
This is the place where
all of your data resides

00:04:50.536 --> 00:04:52.596 A:middle
and you can store that
data, in two different ways.

00:04:53.136 --> 00:04:58.226 A:middle
One is as a private database
and two is as a public database.

00:04:59.026 --> 00:05:02.036 A:middle
Now a private database is
the user's private data.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:59.026 --> 00:05:02.036 A:middle
Now a private database is
the user's private data.

00:05:02.976 --> 00:05:05.226 A:middle
This example would be
the iCloud Photo Library.

00:05:05.396 --> 00:05:08.586 A:middle
All the photos that you
take are stored in CloudKit

00:05:08.996 --> 00:05:11.336 A:middle
and accessible by the user
and managed by the user,

00:05:11.486 --> 00:05:14.046 A:middle
and because it's the
user's private data it comes

00:05:14.046 --> 00:05:17.186 A:middle
out of the user's storage
quota, not the developer's.

00:05:17.186 --> 00:05:19.946 A:middle
Now when we look at
the public database,

00:05:20.386 --> 00:05:22.146 A:middle
this is application's
public data.

00:05:22.696 --> 00:05:25.316 A:middle
A great example of this
is the new News app

00:05:25.496 --> 00:05:27.146 A:middle
that we just announced
yesterday,

00:05:27.606 --> 00:05:30.516 A:middle
where all of those news articles
are actually distributed

00:05:30.516 --> 00:05:33.716 A:middle
to all the news applications
via CloudKit public database

00:05:34.306 --> 00:05:37.016 A:middle
and because it's the
application's public data this

00:05:37.016 --> 00:05:39.436 A:middle
comes out of the
developer's storage quota.

00:05:39.846 --> 00:05:42.936 A:middle
So when we talk about pricing
and we talk about usage,

00:05:42.986 --> 00:05:45.976 A:middle
we are really talking about
public database usage.

00:05:46.766 --> 00:05:47.766 A:middle
So let's see what that means.

00:05:47.766 --> 00:05:51.666 A:middle
For our public database
offering,

00:05:52.066 --> 00:05:53.216 A:middle
we have a free offering.

00:05:54.106 --> 00:05:57.436 A:middle
We also have a fee structure if
you exceed those free limits.

00:05:58.166 --> 00:05:59.856 A:middle
And we also have usage data.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:00.756 --> 00:06:03.956 A:middle
Let's look at the free offering.

00:06:03.956 --> 00:06:08.626 A:middle
So you have to store assets in
the cloud, and we track that

00:06:09.246 --> 00:06:11.066 A:middle
and we give you ten
gigabytes to start.

00:06:11.806 --> 00:06:13.996 A:middle
So if you have no users, you
are just starting development,

00:06:14.376 --> 00:06:14.966 A:middle
10 gigs.

00:06:15.716 --> 00:06:18.296 A:middle
Now as your user
population grows,

00:06:18.296 --> 00:06:21.496 A:middle
as your application becomes more
popular, we are going to grow

00:06:21.496 --> 00:06:24.256 A:middle
with you and we are going to
add an additional 250 megs

00:06:24.256 --> 00:06:27.176 A:middle
for every single user that is
using your application for free

00:06:27.176 --> 00:06:29.186 A:middle
and we will grow that up

00:06:29.296 --> 00:06:32.046 A:middle
to an astonishing 1
petabyte of storage.

00:06:34.156 --> 00:06:36.246 A:middle
Likewise, for the database side,

00:06:36.246 --> 00:06:38.716 A:middle
where you store your record
data, we will start you

00:06:38.716 --> 00:06:42.056 A:middle
with 100 megs and we will
grow that at 2.5 megs per user

00:06:42.056 --> 00:06:44.136 A:middle
and we will go up to
10 terabytes for free.

00:06:45.316 --> 00:06:48.956 A:middle
Now in addition to storage,
we also have data transfer.

00:06:49.756 --> 00:06:50.786 A:middle
So as you're uploading

00:06:50.786 --> 00:06:53.186 A:middle
and downloading your assets
you are consuming bandwidth

00:06:53.236 --> 00:06:56.336 A:middle
and we will start
you with 2 gigabytes

00:06:56.596 --> 00:06:59.106 A:middle
of data transfer per
month in and out.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:00.076 --> 00:07:02.856 A:middle
And like the others we will grow
that as you have more users.

00:07:02.856 --> 00:07:05.066 A:middle
So we will add an extra 50
megs per user per month.

00:07:05.166 --> 00:07:08.996 A:middle
And we will allow you to
grow up to 200 terabytes

00:07:09.096 --> 00:07:11.936 A:middle
of data transfer per
month all for free.

00:07:12.686 --> 00:07:15.856 A:middle
Now for database, it's
a little different.

00:07:16.356 --> 00:07:19.106 A:middle
We actually measure it on
a request per second basis.

00:07:19.106 --> 00:07:20.716 A:middle
So we are going to start you

00:07:20.716 --> 00:07:22.976 A:middle
at 40 requests per second,
which is very large.

00:07:23.816 --> 00:07:25.486 A:middle
And just like the
others, we will grow

00:07:26.416 --> 00:07:27.486 A:middle
with the number of users.

00:07:27.856 --> 00:07:29.126 A:middle
And we will do that
in increments

00:07:29.126 --> 00:07:31.976 A:middle
of 10 requests per second
for each 100,000 users

00:07:32.356 --> 00:07:36.386 A:middle
up to 400 requests per second
for free, and what's important

00:07:36.386 --> 00:07:38.386 A:middle
to note about the
request per second is

00:07:38.386 --> 00:07:39.686 A:middle
that it's actually
a throttle limit.

00:07:40.346 --> 00:07:42.976 A:middle
So if for some reason your
application hits these limits,

00:07:42.976 --> 00:07:46.176 A:middle
we will actually send you
back a throttling error back

00:07:46.176 --> 00:07:47.926 A:middle
to your client to tell
you you've hit the limits.

00:07:48.476 --> 00:07:50.696 A:middle
And then we will talk
in a bit about how

00:07:50.696 --> 00:07:52.666 A:middle
to make sure that
doesn't happen.

00:07:53.496 --> 00:07:54.706 A:middle
All right.

00:07:54.796 --> 00:07:56.746 A:middle
Now, if you do go
over those limits,

00:07:56.866 --> 00:07:58.226 A:middle
there is a way to pay for more.

00:07:58.546 --> 00:08:00.216 A:middle
And that's our public
database fees.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.546 --> 00:08:00.216 A:middle
And that's our public
database fees.

00:08:01.266 --> 00:08:03.406 A:middle
Now, this is over and above
what we give you for free.

00:08:03.406 --> 00:08:06.476 A:middle
So it's the incremental delta
between what you get for free,

00:08:06.836 --> 00:08:07.706 A:middle
and what you are using.

00:08:08.456 --> 00:08:11.536 A:middle
So for assets, it's $0.03
per gigabyte per month,

00:08:12.226 --> 00:08:14.136 A:middle
for database, $3.00
per gig per month.

00:08:14.876 --> 00:08:16.066 A:middle
On the transfer side,

00:08:16.276 --> 00:08:18.416 A:middle
for transferring
assets $0.10 per gig

00:08:19.146 --> 00:08:20.886 A:middle
and on the database
request rates,

00:08:21.226 --> 00:08:23.946 A:middle
we'll add an extra 10
requests per second for $100,

00:08:24.276 --> 00:08:26.726 A:middle
and so you can increment that
number up to get to the level

00:08:26.726 --> 00:08:29.106 A:middle
that allows your
application to work smoothly

00:08:29.106 --> 00:08:30.266 A:middle
if you hit the free limits.

00:08:30.796 --> 00:08:35.726 A:middle
And, of course, push is free.

