00:15:01.476 --> 00:15:02.546 A:middle
So how does this work?

00:15:03.266 --> 00:15:04.716 A:middle
Well, first lets talk
about the features.

00:15:04.716 --> 00:15:09.016 A:middle
You get a full CloudKit
API via JSON and HTTPS,

00:15:09.826 --> 00:15:12.346 A:middle
we also provide CloudKit
JS Library

00:15:12.346 --> 00:15:13.806 A:middle
which is absolutely the best way

00:15:13.856 --> 00:15:15.696 A:middle
to quickly create
web applications,

00:15:16.566 --> 00:15:19.126 A:middle
and we provide Web Sign in
with Apple ID is the way

00:15:19.126 --> 00:15:20.606 A:middle
that your users will
authenticate

00:15:20.606 --> 00:15:22.566 A:middle
when they use your web app.

00:15:24.496 --> 00:15:25.566 A:middle
Now, how does this work?

00:15:25.566 --> 00:15:30.116 A:middle
If you look today, you'll
see your application running

00:15:30.256 --> 00:15:32.146 A:middle
on iOS and OS X.

00:15:32.146 --> 00:15:34.076 A:middle
It interacts with
CloudKit the framework,

00:15:34.496 --> 00:15:36.946 A:middle
which behind the scenes talks
to our CloudKit servers.

00:15:38.276 --> 00:15:42.186 A:middle
What we have introduced
today is the ability for you

00:15:42.186 --> 00:15:43.886 A:middle
to create your own
web application,

00:15:43.886 --> 00:15:47.896 A:middle
running in a web browser and
talking over JSON and HTTPS,

00:15:48.746 --> 00:15:51.666 A:middle
to our CloudKit Web Services
which lets you then talk

00:15:51.766 --> 00:15:54.256 A:middle
to the same exact
CloudKit servers

00:15:54.626 --> 00:15:57.526 A:middle
that your native applications
are talking to on iOS and OS X.

00:15:57.526 --> 00:16:00.726 A:middle
Now, it's important to
understand about the JSON

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:57.526 --> 00:16:00.726 A:middle
Now, it's important to
understand about the JSON

00:16:00.726 --> 00:16:04.026 A:middle
and the HTTPS piece of this,
it's just a specification.

00:16:04.706 --> 00:16:05.576 A:middle
There's no code.

00:16:06.206 --> 00:16:08.006 A:middle
Effectively, it's up to
you as a developer to look

00:16:08.006 --> 00:16:09.116 A:middle
at that specification.

00:16:09.746 --> 00:16:12.526 A:middle
You get to construct your own
end points, hitting endpoints.

00:16:12.836 --> 00:16:16.216 A:middle
You get to create your URLs and
construct your JSONs that goes

00:16:16.216 --> 00:16:19.426 A:middle
in the bodies that go up in
a request, you get back JSON

00:16:19.426 --> 00:16:22.436 A:middle
in responses, you parse that,
you deal with asset uploads

00:16:22.436 --> 00:16:24.766 A:middle
and downloads, retry
logic and on and on.

00:16:25.216 --> 00:16:28.846 A:middle
But a much better way to do
this is using the CloudKit

00:16:29.166 --> 00:16:30.296 A:middle
JS framework.

00:16:30.996 --> 00:16:34.836 A:middle
CloudKit JS gives you a
JavaScript API that you can use

00:16:35.016 --> 00:16:38.126 A:middle
that shields you from all
the complexities of the HTTPS

00:16:38.126 --> 00:16:40.676 A:middle
and JSON protocol
that sits behind it.

00:16:41.046 --> 00:16:43.856 A:middle
And you can use either one,
but you are probably crazy

00:16:43.856 --> 00:16:44.656 A:middle
if you go the other route.

00:16:44.656 --> 00:16:46.806 A:middle
So please use CloudKit JS.

00:16:47.896 --> 00:16:49.206 A:middle
So what does this give you?

00:16:49.466 --> 00:16:51.026 A:middle
Well all right, it
gives you full public

00:16:51.026 --> 00:16:52.436 A:middle
and private database access.

00:16:53.036 --> 00:16:54.846 A:middle
It gives you all those
record applications.

00:16:55.316 --> 00:16:57.266 A:middle
It lets you upload
and download assets.

00:16:57.736 --> 00:16:59.566 A:middle
It lets you execute queries.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:00.406 --> 00:17:03.086 A:middle
It even lets you do
subscriptions and notifications,

00:17:03.536 --> 00:17:06.976 A:middle
which means that I can actually
get an asynchronous event

00:17:07.076 --> 00:17:09.726 A:middle
into my web application,
just like you get pushes

00:17:09.935 --> 00:17:12.406 A:middle
to tell you something has
changed or to notify you

00:17:12.526 --> 00:17:14.476 A:middle
of some other event,
so you don't have

00:17:14.476 --> 00:17:16.796 A:middle
to have users hitting the
refresh button or pulling

00:17:16.796 --> 00:17:17.896 A:middle
from your web application.

00:17:18.925 --> 00:17:20.586 A:middle
It also has user
discoverability,

00:17:21.445 --> 00:17:23.876 A:middle
and it has the ability to answer
the question what's changed

00:17:23.876 --> 00:17:26.695 A:middle
since within custom zones
which gives you sync semantics.

00:17:27.346 --> 00:17:31.336 A:middle
In short, what this gives
you is full compatibility

00:17:31.336 --> 00:17:32.806 A:middle
and capability as what you get

00:17:33.186 --> 00:17:40.316 A:middle
on the native CloudKit
on iOS and OS X.

00:17:40.836 --> 00:17:44.896 A:middle
Now, CloudKit JS, as I mentioned
before is the absolute best way

00:17:44.896 --> 00:17:46.196 A:middle
to develop web applications.

00:17:46.196 --> 00:17:47.246 A:middle
It's a JavaScript API.

00:17:48.296 --> 00:17:50.756 A:middle
It matches the native
CloudKit API as much

00:17:50.756 --> 00:17:52.746 A:middle
as you can make JavaScript
match Objective-C,

00:17:52.746 --> 00:17:54.456 A:middle
but you know we did our
best, it's pretty close.

00:17:55.106 --> 00:17:56.566 A:middle
There's no intermediate servers.

00:17:56.566 --> 00:17:59.316 A:middle
So you can create your
JavaScript application

00:17:59.626 --> 00:18:02.266 A:middle
and you can talk directly
to the CloudKit, you know --

